{"title_page": "Thoughts on Government", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Thoughts on Government.jpg|thumb|The book ''Thoughts on Government'' by John Adams (1776)]]\n'''''Thoughts on Government''''', or in full '''''Thoughts on Government, Applicable to the Present State of the American Colonies''''', was written by [[John Adams]] during the spring of 1776 in response to a resolution of the [[North Carolina Provincial Congress]] which requested Adams' suggestions on the establishment of a new [[government]] and the drafting of a [[constitution]]. Adams says that \"Politics is the Science of human Happiness -and the Felicity of Societies depends on the Constitutions of Government under which they live.\" Many of the ideas put forth in Adams' [[essay]] were adopted in December 1776 by the framers of [[Constitution of North Carolina#Constitution of 1776|North Carolina's first constitution]].\n\nThe document is notable in that Adams sketches out the three branches of American government: the [[Federal government of the United States#Executive branch|executive]], [[Federal government of the United States#Judicial branch|judicial]], and [[Federal government of the United States#The legislative branch|legislative branches]], all with a system of [[Separation of powers|checks and balances]].  Furthermore, in response to [[Common Sense (pamphlet)|''Common Sense'']] by [[Thomas Paine]], Adams rejects the idea of [[unicameralism|a single legislative body]], fearing it may become tyrannical or self-serving (as in the case of the [[Dutch Republic|Netherlands]] at the time).  Thus, Adams also conceived of the idea that two legislative bodies should serve as checks to the power of the other.<ref>''[[John Adams (book)|John Adams]]'' by [[David McCullough]], Simon and Schuster Paperbacks, New York, 2001.  Pg 102-103. {{ISBN|978-0-684-81363-9}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[John_Adams#Thoughts_on_Government]]\n*[[Constitutionalism]]\n*[[Rule according to higher law]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Thoughts on Government|''Thoughts on Government''}}\n\n{{John Adams}}\n{{American Revolution origins|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thoughts On Government}}\n[[Category:1776 books]]\n[[Category:Books in political philosophy]]\n[[Category:Constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Documents of the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:18th-century essays]]\n[[Category:John Adams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Thoughts on Government.jpg|thumb|The book ''Thoughts on Government'' by John Adams (1776)]]\n'''''Thoughts on Government''''', or in full '''''Thoughts on Government, Applicable to the Present State of the American Colonies''''', was written by [[John Adams]] during the spring of 1776 in response to a resolution of the [[North Carolina Provincial Congress]] which requested Adams' suggestions on the establishment of a new [[government]] and the drafting of a [[constitution]]. Adams says that \"Politics is the Science of human Happiness -and the Felicity of Societies depends on the Constitutions of Government under which they live.\" Many of the ideas put forth in Adams' [[essay]] were adopted in December 1776 by the framers of [[Constitution of North Carolina#Constitution of 1776|North Carolina's first constitution]].\n\nThe document is notable in that Adams sketches out the three branches of American government: the [[Federal government of the United States#Executive branch|executive]], [[Federal government of the United States#Judicial branch|judicial]], and [[Federal government of the United States#The legislative branch|legislative branches]], all with a system of [[Separation of powers|checks and balances]].  Furthermore, in response to [[Common Sense (pamphlet)|''Common Sense'']] by [[Thomas Paine]], Adams rejects the idea of [[unicameralism|a single legislative body]], fearing it may become tyrannical or self-serving (as in the case of the [[Dutch Republic|Netherlands]] at the time).  Thus, Adams also conceived of the idea that two legislative bodies should serve as checks to the power of the other.<ref>''[[John Adams (book)|John Adams]]'' by [[David McCullough]], Simon and Schuster Paperbacks, New York, 2001.  Pg 102-103. {{ISBN|978-0-684-81363-9}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Constitutionalism]]\n*[[Rule according to higher law]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Thoughts on Government|''Thoughts on Government''}}\n\n{{John Adams}}\n{{American Revolution origins|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thoughts On Government}}\n[[Category:1776 books]]\n[[Category:Books in political philosophy]]\n[[Category:Constitutional law]]\n[[Category:Documents of the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:18th-century essays]]\n[[Category:John Adams]]\n", "name_user": "Robert Loring", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Added a link to John Adams' main page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thoughts_on_Government"}
